# gen108 (L13): ordered procedure to a goal — a tiny planner. Prerequisites are
# taught as requires(Goal, Step) facts in ANY order; "how do I make X?" returns a
# correctly ORDERED plan, derived by a depth-first topological sort of the
# dependency DAG so every step precedes what depends on it. The sequence is never
# stored — it is recomputed from the scattered facts (anti-impostor: the order is
# reasoned, not recited). Held-out goals.

# Teach the prerequisites SCRAMBLED — deliberately not in any usable order.
> batter requires eggs
< Learned: requires(batter, eggs).
> cake requires batter
< Learned: requires(cake, batter).
> cake requires oven
< Learned: requires(cake, oven).
> batter requires flour
< Learned: requires(batter, flour).
# The plan comes out correctly ordered: eggs and flour (no prereqs) before
# batter (which needs them), batter and oven before cake. Never taught as a list.
> how do I make cake?
< To make cake: eggs, flour, batter, oven, then cake.
# The justification is the ordering principle itself, derived from the facts.
> how do you know?
< Because ordered by prerequisites: each step follows everything it requires.

# A transitive chain orders correctly too: kettle before hot_water before tea.
> tea requires hot_water
< Learned: requires(tea, hot_water).
> hot_water requires kettle
< Learned: requires(hot_water, kettle).
> tea requires cup
< Learned: requires(tea, cup).
> how do I make tea?
< To make tea: kettle, hot_water, cup, then tea.

# A goal with no known prerequisites is honestly unknown — no invented steps.
> how do I make pizza?
< I don't know the steps to make pizza yet.

# A circular prerequisite cannot be ordered — say so rather than loop or guess.
> loopa requires loopb
< Learned: requires(loopa, loopb).
> loopb requires loopa
< Learned: requires(loopb, loopa).
> how do I make loopa?
< The steps for loopa have a circular prerequisite — I can't order them.